<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-357-43> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Nuu-chah-nulth (Nootka) model whaling canoe; ca. 1860-1880\r\nWood; paint; l. 110 cm., w. 21 cm.\r\nRMV 357-43; museum purchase from dealer A.P. Goodwin, 1882\r\n\r\nThe canoe, whether designed for fishing, sealing, whaling or war, is at the heart of Nuu-chah-nulth culture. Their canoe design is like artistry in wood.\r\n\r\nThis model of a Nootka canoe or chapac (ch’apats) was acquired in 1882 from the Danish taxidermist, photographer and dealer in natural history specimens A.P. Goodwin. The bow of the model rises higher than in mid-century and earlier canoes, making it contemporary with a collection date of circa 1860-1880. Models are not strictly to scale, but it is possible to expand this 110 centimeter one to a real-life one of 31,5 foot long by 5 foot wide whaling canoe or pinwal (barrel), or in southern Nootka, ?o?o’taxsac (?o?o:taxsats; cf. Arima and Hoover 2011:57).\r\nThe four occupants are carved in one piece with the boat to enhance market value. The painted decoration by U-filler shapes is simpler than in several finer museum specimens thought to be earlier made model canoes (cf. Black 1999:114-116). Thwarts are lacking, but the bottom has the skeg-like blades at its ends that are essential to proper handling. There are several classes of Nootka canoes ranging from about just 8 feet to over fifty feet: the 18 feet commercial sealer, the 24 feet sealing canoe, the 28 to 38 feet whaling canoe, and war canoes of similar size.\r\nThe Nootka design is minimalist but has a “nose” to the prow with a slight “heart” bump below for animal symbolism. It is usually without painted decoration except perhaps for collar-like stripes at the bow and the stern. The latter is often carved in the shape of an animal’s head, thought to symbolize a deer with upturned ears. In this model it is not defined as such. Carving of and painting on the bow is often interpreted as representative of Wolf, an important figure in Nuu-chah-nulth belief and ritual.\r\n Balancing stability, speed, capacity, and low wind resistance, the seaworthy style was copied in its bigger whaling and voyaging forms by several open Pacific coast neighbors: to the north the Quatsino and Koksimo who are Kwakwaka’wakw, and to the south the Quileute and Quinault. Thus the Nootka canoe is made along some 500 km. of the West coast from the northwest end of Vancouver Island to near Gray’s Harbor in southwest Washington State. Moreover, Nootka canoes were widely traded to Salish and other peoples of Juan de Fuca Strait, Georgia Strait, Puget Sound, and Oregon.\r\nWhaling was important to the Nuu-chah-nulth in whose territory salmon streams are of much lesser consequence than elsewhere on the Northwest coast. Whether their whaling canoe had northern origins (Inuit, Aleut) or was an indigenous development is still debated. Influences of the Salish canoe on the shape of the stern are obvious (Arima 2000).\r\n\r\nEugene Arima; 2015\r\nem. Canadian Museum of Civilization, Ottawa\r\n\r\nEugene Arima, Thoughts on the Nuu-chah-nulth Canoe; in: Alan L. Hoover, ed., Nuu-chah-nulth Voices, Histories, Objects and Journeys: 306-329; Royal British Columbia Museum; Victoria, 2000. Eugene Arima and Alan Hoover, The Whaling People of the West Coast of Vancouver Island and Cape Flattery; Royal British Columbia Museum; Victoria, 2011. Martha Black, Out of the Mist: Treasures of the Nuu-chah-nulth Chiefs; Royal British Columbia Museum; Victoria, 1999.\r\n\r\n\r\nModel van een kano voor de walvisjacht\r\nKanomodellen\r\nMiniaturisering van de wereld kwam vaak tot uiting in kinderspeelgoed. Voor jongens werden kanomodellen gesneden om mee te spelen. Miniaturisering speelde ook in op het ontstaan van een externe blanke markt voor souvenirs, en modellen van kano's waren een populair artikel, zeker als deze voorzien waren van een of meer menselijke figuurtjes en/of beschildering van de romp. De figuurtjes stelden vaak vissers voor, of een huwelijkspaar met begeleiders. Zij waren uit één stuk samen met de boot gesneden of vormden losse elementen. Ook miniatuur peddels maakten er deel van uit, maar dan als losse stukken. Vanwege hun natuurgetrouwheid in de geminiaturiseerdse reproductie komen de verschillende kanotypes en kunststijlen van de Noordwest kust tot uiting. Opvallend zijn de kano's van de Nootkas en Makahs met hun schuin vooruitspringende boegspriet die zo gesneden is dat deze doet denken aan de kop van een dier. Het noordelijke type is veel minder elegant en meer zwaarwichtig. Ook de vaareigenschappen zijn beperkter. De modellen werden in alle soorten kwaliteit gemaakt, van artistieke kunstwerkjes tot ruwe massaproductie.\r\n\r\nBehalve tribale stijlen waren er ook verschillende types naar gebruik: voor walvisjacht, voor oorlogvoering, voor jacht op zeehonden.\r\n\r\nDe betekenis van de op de Nootka kano's geschilderde motieven is niet bekend. De boegbeschildering wordt wel geassocieerd met de wolf en de de motieven op de achterkant met het hert." .
